<paragraph blockId="6.[168,776,1213,1746]" pageId="6" pageNumber="321">
relatively small body size, compared to its congeners, such as 
<taxonomicName box="[257,392,1247,1271]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Clariidae" genus="Clarias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="321" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis box="[257,392,1247,1271]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="321">C. orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[448,552,1247,1270]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Clariidae" genus="Clarias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="321" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="striata">
<emphasis box="[448,552,1247,1270]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="321">C. striata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. There is significant evidence suggesting 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hamilton" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[393,504,1280,1304]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Channidae" genus="Channa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="321" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gachua">
<emphasis box="[393,504,1280,1304]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="321">C. gachua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a complex of species, and a taxonomic review of this group is clearly necessary. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ng HH &amp; Ng PKL &amp; Britz R" box="[168,341,1348,1373]" pageId="6" pageNumber="321" pagination="57 - 63" refId="ref8828" refString="Ng HH, Ng PKL, Britz R (1999) Channa harcourtbutleri (Annandale, 1918): a valid species of snakehead (Perciformes: Channidae) from Myanmar. Journal of South Asian Natural History 4 (1): 57 - 63." type="journal article" year="1999">Ng et al. (1999)</bibRefCitation>
noted the presence of small black spots on the body of Indochinese specimens but not on those from 
<collectingCountry box="[232,287,1416,1440]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="321">India</collectingCountry>
and from Greater Sunda Islands. Notwith- standing, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tan HH &amp; Ng PKL" box="[274,483,1450,1475]" pageId="6" pageNumber="321" pagination="115 - 138" refId="ref9567" refString="Tan HH, Ng PKL (2005) The labyrinth fishes (Teleostei: Anabanatoidei, Channoidei) of Sumatra, Indonesia. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, Supplement 13: 115 - 138." type="journal article" year="2005">Tan and Ng (2005)</bibRefCitation>
later observed this similar color pattern on specimens also from Jambi province, Sumatra. They are usually found in hill streams, while the adults inhabit medium-sized to large rivers, brooks, rapid-running mountain streams, and stagnant water bod- ies including sluggish flowing canals (
<bibRefCitation author="Taki Y" box="[585,700,1620,1644]" pageId="6" pageNumber="321" refId="ref9492" refString="Taki Y (1978) An analytical study of the fish fauna of the Mekong basin as a biological production system in nature. Research Institute of Evolutionary Biology Special Publications No 1. Research Institute of Evolutionary Biology, Tokyo, 77 pp." type="book" year="1978">Taki 1978</bibRefCitation>
). They feed at night on small fish, insects, and crustaceans. They exhibit parental care, with the male brooding eggs and fry in his mouth (
<bibRefCitation author="Lim KKP &amp; Tan HH &amp; Low JKY" box="[315,482,1722,1746]" pageId="6" pageNumber="321" refId="ref8278" refString="Lim KKP, Tan HH, Low JKY (2008) Fishes. In: Davison GWH, Ng PKL, Chew HH (Eds) The Singapore Red Data Book: Threatened Plants and Animals of Singapore. 2 nd ed. Nature Society, Singa- pore, 285 pp." type="book" year="2008">Lim et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
)
</paragraph>
